Preheat your #oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pour the @water for the rice{200%ml} into a #medium saucepan with a tight-fitting
#lid. Stir in the @jasmine rice{100%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil.
Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered)
and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice
will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @butternut squash{1}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the
seeds (peel first if you prefer). Cut into 2cm chunks.

Pop the diced butternut onto a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{1%tbsp},
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then sprinkle over the @Thai style spice mix{1}.

> Add less spice if you'd prefer things milder.

Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer and sprinkle over the
@black sesame seeds{5}.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and cooked through,
~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Peel and grate
the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Zest and cut the @lime{1/2} into wedges.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan on medium-high heat. Once hot,
add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and shallot and cook until browned
all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging.

Add the garlic and @Thai green curry paste{45%g}. Fry, stirring, for
~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @coconut milk{200%ml} and
@water for the sauce{50%ml}. Bring to a boil, then turn the heat down to medium
and simmer, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir through the @peas{120%g} and cook until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Meanwhile, once the rice is cooked, fluff up the rice using a #fork. Stir
through the lime zest.

Once the curry sauce has thickened, taste and season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and
@sugar{} (if you have any) if needed. Remove from the heat and add a squeeze of
lime juice.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add half of the roasted black sesame butternut to the curry and stir until
coated, adding a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share the zesty rice between your #bowls{}.

Spoon the Thai green style curry over the rice and top with the remaining
roasted black sesame butternut.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!